&nbsp;AGI - Over 330 thousand plants planted, 211 redeveloped green areas, forest restoration, biodiversity protection: a sum of interventions able to generate a total economic and social benefit of the value of more than 1 million and 700 thousand euros for each year of life of the arboreal and arbustive plants put to abode. These are just some of the data presented during the event “Ecosystem Mosaico” held in Rome for the sixth birthday of Mosaico Verde, the national campaign for the foresting of green areas>, the recovery of ecosystems and environmental regeneration, promoted by AzzeroCO2 and Legambiente. The event is part of the calendar of events of the Festival of Sustainable Development 2024, > promoted by ASVIS.
&nbsp;
The conference was also the occasion to illustrate the eco-system vision of the Campaign, which ranges from the regeneration of the woods and the urban green areas to the protection and restoration of the different natural habitats, always keeping the attention on the specificities of the individual territories and involving in the project all stakeholders (institutions, associations, local committees, employees, residents). So far 50 companies have chosen to support Mosaico Verde>, integrating it into their own strategies of Corporate Social Responsibility.>&nbsp;
Companies today recognize that giving concrete and targeted contributions to counter climate change and redevelopment of the territories is not only fundamental to the health of the planet, but also indispensable if they want to improve and consolidate the relationship with their stakeholders.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
“In a global context marked by increasingly urgent environmental challenges, the protection of biodiversity and ecosystems emerges as a fundamental defence line. Their loss results in both an unparalleled ecological crisis and a direct risk for the welfare of the community. In these six years, the Campaign has traced a path that has led it from being an ambitious reforestation project to an integrated model of protection and enhancement of ecosystems. Thanks to the companies that have believed in this project, we have redeveloped more than 3,3 million square meters of green areas,> with the involvement of more than 122 municipalities and 32 Park Enti in 17 different Italian regions: every intervention is unique, but it supports a common goal of resilience and sustainability," said Sandro Scollato, CEO of AzzeroCO2,> company founded by Legambiente and Kyoto Club and that this year celebrates its first twenty years of activity.
&nbsp;
The event was attended by Ilaria Capua>, a internationally acclaimed virologa and essayist, professor at Johns Hopkins University SAIS Europe. His speech focused on the theme “More health: a way of thinking” highlighted how ‘Circular health’ > is a systemic approach based on the One Health paradigm, recognizing, in addition, the need for a multidisciplinary convergence effort that goes beyond the biomedical dimension of health. Circular health uses sustainable development goals such as implementation tools and Big data as a source of new information.
&nbsp;
In view of the alarming figures provided by the Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES), which indicates that about 75% of the Earth's environment and 66% of the marine environment have been significantly altered by human action, it is more than ever impelling to act for effective protection of biodiversity.' The goal of Green Mosaic is to support the territories in preserving threatened ecosystems, preventing fires and protecting landscapes by restoring natural balance.
&nbsp;
Preserving ecosystems also means protecting against threats - daughters of climate change >– plants and native crops, which today suffer attacks from parasitic agents or have been affected by diseases that put entire secular cultures at risk. This is an example of the initiative carried out in Puglia in collaboration with Unaprol and which supports an experimental project that aims to strengthen the resistance of monumental olive trees, thanks to grafts with varieties more resistant to the bacterium Xylella Fastidiosa.
&nbsp;
In the same way, increasing efforts to prevent fires and protecting affected landscapes is fundamental to safeguard the Italian ecosystem. In only 2023, from 15 June to 15 September, numerous forest fires devastated almost 75,000 hectares of territory in Italy, 11,000 of which were covered by forest ecosystems (Dati Ispra). These data highlight how crucial it is not only to prevent such disasters, but also to focus on regeneration of affected areas: an example of the interventions made in Sardinia, in the Montiferro region.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Albero after tree we arrived at the sixth edition of Green Mosaic - said Stefano Ciafani, national president of Legambiente -. A campaign that turns out year by year to be a powerful ally in contrast to the climate crisis that increasingly threatens our territories, biodiversity and habitats, stealing our future. Over 330 thousand plants planted throughout Italy in these years of commitment and activism, which allowed us to recover the green of our cities, restore social spaces, recreate natural oasis of biodiversity and protect the Italian ecological wealth. An incredible work, which also supported the European Life Earth project of which Legambiente is the only Italian representative, and which shows us that union makes strength if the enemy to beat is the climate crisis and the goal is a sustainable, fairer and fairer future."
&nbsp;
The care of ecosystems is therefore a responsibility, but also an extraordinary opportunity to enrich and preserve the natural heritage and work for a sustainable future.
In pursuing this goal, Green Mosaic has never been alone: the created synergies have been and continue to be the true added value. In these years, the contribution of companies and agencies that have joined the campaign has been decisive and has shown that a world can be built in which balance with nature is not a utopia, but a reality within the reach of all.
